==Old English==
===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*kokar-'', from Hunnic ''*kukur''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[koker]], Old Saxon [[kokar]] (Dutch [[koker]]), Old High German [[kohhar|kohhār]] (German [[Köcher]]).  There are also cognates in many Turkic languages, including Altay [[кӧкӧр]], Kazakh [[көккөр]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'koker/

===Noun===
'''cocer''' ''m''
# a [[quiver]] for arrows

